.Use the Hugging Face CLI login method first. It is safer than putting the token directly into your script or command. Your token should be a read-only or fine-grained read token, since the autocoder only downloads models and does not upload anything. Hugging Face’s docs describe read tokens as sufficient for downloading/reading model content, and fine-grained tokens as useful when you want to restrict access to specific resources.  

Recommended method: log in once from Positron

Open Positron Terminal and run:

cd C:\laborshed_autocode
.\.venv\Scripts\Activate.ps1
python -m pip install -U huggingface_hub

Set the Hugging Face cache location for this project:

setx HF_HOME "C:\laborshed_autocode\hf_cache"
setx HF_HUB_CACHE "C:\laborshed_autocode\hf_cache\hub"
setx HF_HUB_DISABLE_PROGRESS_BARS "1"

Close and reopen the Positron terminal so the setx changes load.

Then run:

cd C:\laborshed_autocode
.\.venv\Scripts\Activate.ps1
hf auth login

Paste your Hugging Face token when prompted.

When it asks about Git credentials, choose:

n

You are not pushing models to Hugging Face. You only need model downloads.

Verify login:

hf auth whoami

Hugging Face documents hf auth login as the CLI login command, and HF_HOME / HF_HUB_CACHE as the locations used for token/cache storage.  

If hf is not recognized

Try:

python -m pip install -U huggingface_hub[cli]
hf auth login

If hf still is not recognized, use the older fallback command:

huggingface-cli login

Then verify:

huggingface-cli whoami

Session-only method, if you do not want to store the token

This only applies to the current Positron terminal window. It disappears when the terminal closes.

Run:

$secure = Read-Host "Paste Hugging Face token" -AsSecureString
$ptr = [Runtime.InteropServices.Marshal]::SecureStringToBSTR($secure)
try {
    $env:HF_TOKEN = [Runtime.InteropServices.Marshal]::PtrToStringBSTR($ptr)
} finally {
    [Runtime.InteropServices.Marshal]::ZeroFreeBSTR($ptr)
}

Then run the autocoder from that same terminal.

Do not do this:

$env:HF_TOKEN = ""

An empty HF_TOKEN can override the token saved on the machine. Hugging Face documents that HF_TOKEN, when set, overrides the token stored at the normal token path.  

Persistent environment-variable method

This is useful if SPSS 26 launches Python and you want the token always available to that external Python process.

Run:

setx HF_TOKEN "hf_your_token_here"

Then close and reopen Positron, PowerShell, and SPSS.

I only recommend this if IT is comfortable storing the token as a Windows user environment variable. The CLI login method is usually cleaner.

